author: itsnotshade
body:
Thinking EPS is that much more significant than forward looking. Rookie mistake. Hitting expected EPS is a good starting point for adjusting forward looking statements for analysts, but earnings can be windfalls, seasonal, etc. This is the same story with HPQ. Business shot up thanks to covid but it's looking a little dry going forward. 

You should have known that the price target would drop significantly after EVERY "covid economy" success story has either been slowly dropping over the last few weeks or stayed totally flat while industrials, B&M retailers, and service companies have skyrocketed.

Peloton anyone? That was about to hit $50. Look at it now. Logitech, ZM, Chegg have stayed almost totally flat  since Jpow's "we digitally print money" miracle.

author: spacegrab
body:
- This parts shortage is normal. 5000+ endpoints in my IT area, 90% Dell. I experience shortages on a normal basis as chipsets or CPUs run into logistical problems or when they move to new models. This isn't fucking new. I had to wait 3 months for a monitor replacement cuz India kept fucking up my tickets even with my regional rep helping me out.

- If anything, their supply chain issues are resolved. Demand is LOW right now. I bought several WD19TB laptop docks last week and it showed up in 2 days. These fuckers were on 3-4 week delay back in April.

- Most Enterprise IT teams worth their salt have already finished scrambling to accomodate most users for WFH. 

- I fucking posted this shit yesterday and called HPQ short. Some idiots saw the EPS beat and started beating off on stocktwits despite the CRAZY BAD reports across ALL segments. 

> Down 31% on commercial devices.

> Down 15% on ink supplies.

> Down 19% on printing division overall.

> Down 16% on consumer hardware (despite 5% laptop uptick).

- Dell isn't as shitty, like seriously FUCK HP laptops. I like Dell's business line though. It's possible they trade sideways or even profit, but I'm really skeptical after seeing WDC, PLT, and HPQ's sentiments on ER this quarter. -

- I'm guessing Dell might have a 10% uptick in laptop sales but overall guidance is going to be trash.

Dell 40p 6/19
